                <head>No. 230.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Noyes</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-06-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 17, 1881</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 384.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                    dispatch No. 475, of <pb facs="0537" n="413" xml:id="pg_413"/> the 27th ultimo,
                    in reply to the telegram of the Department of the 24th ultimo, in reference to
                    certain published statements alleged to have been made by the minister of
                    commerce on the subject of trichinae in America.</p>
                <p>In reply, I have to say that the Department learns with satisfaction that Mr.
                    Tirard, the minister of commerce, did not make the statements attributed to him,
                    and that it seems probable that the decree prohibiting the importation of
                    American pork into France may soon be revoked.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JAMES G. BLAINE.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
